The United States warned Iran again that it was ready to retaliate for any further hostile militaryaction in the Gulf as U.S. warships began escorting anothertanker convoy southward from Kuwait.    U.S. Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger said the U.S.sought no further Gulf hostitilies but was ready to deal withany Iranian response to Monday's attack on an Iranian oil rig.    Several hours later, the Pentagon announced that U.S.warships had begun escorting two U.S. flag Kuwaiti tankers --the 80,000 ton product carrier Ocean City and 46,000 tonliquified petroleum tanker Gas King -- southward from Kuwait.    The Defense Department said the 12th such convoy of U.S.flagged Kuwaiti tankers through the Gulf began at 0230 EDTunder the escort by the U.S. guided missile frigate Ford. Itdid not say what oth U.S. warships were in the area.    "It (the convoy) is now progressing uneventfully in thecentral Gulf," the Pentagon statement said.    Asked on NBC's "Today" program if the United States wasprepared for a major war with Iran, Weinberger said, "Well weare prepared I think for whatever eventualities emerge fromthis situation but we don't look on it as a war." REUTER&#3;